@EndNode

@Node New "New versions"
@{u}How to obtain the latest version of NetGate@{uu}

NetGate is available from any AmiNet mirror, for example ftp.wustl.edu,
ftp.doc.ic.ac.uk or ftp.luth.se. For example:

AmiNet:comm/net/netgat13.lha

If you prefer a FidoNet File Request, the latest version of the program may
be requested from 2:238/24.0 under the magic name NETGATE.
@EndNode

@Node History "History"
@{u}History@{uu}

Below is a listing of the most signifficant changes in this and previous
versions of the program. The most recent version is listed first.

Date        Version   Notes
----        -------   -----

06.10.96    1.3       Added automatic notification of new newsgroups as they
                      are created on your news server. See the new
                      @{"NOSCANNEWGROUPS" LINK NOSCANNEWGROUPS} and @{"SCANNEWGROUPSFILTER" LINK SCANNEWGROUPSFILTER} keywords.

                      When sending e-mails NetGate now includes the e-mail
                      address of each receiver in the log output.

                      Fixed a bug that could cause mail packets to be deleted
                      from your outbound directory if a connection to the news
                      or mail server could not be established.

                      Added @{"REPLYTO" LINK REPLYTO} keyword.

                      Improved timeout error handling when sending mail.

                      Included all-new @{"NGWatch" LINK NGWatch} utility.

                      Added @{"TIMEOUT" LINK TIMEOUT} preferences keyword (default is 30 seconds)

                      Moderated newsgroups have not worked since the
                      release which included the new mailing list features.
                      Very few people must be using this feature, or it
                      would have been reported months ago :-) Fixed.

                      NetGate now looks for the configuration file in the
                      ConfigPath environment variable and in Mail: before
                      giving up. (So the order is: PROGDIR, ENV, ConfigPath,
                      Mail:, ENVARC:)

                      NetGate did not always escape a single dot (.) on a
                      line by itself, which could cause various problems.
                      Fixed.

                      Added support for NNTP authentication, as required by
                      some servers. New keyword: @{"NNTPAUTH/K/A,USERID/A,PASS/A" LINK NNTPAuth}.
                      Note: Do not use this unless your news server
                      actually requires it.

                      Enforcer hit when connecting to some SMTP servers fixed.

                      Added a @{"DEBUG" LINK Usage} switch.

                      NetGate now uses quoted-printable rather than 8bit encoding
                      when posting news articles.

                      Normal UseNet news headers are now correctly appended
                      when sending mailing list "articles". Previous versions
                      would fail to pick up and include things like organization
                      and x-newsreader.

                      Added support for @{"file attachments" LINK FAttach}. This new facility
                      enables you to send and receive files over the Internet
                      just like normal Fidonet attachments. Uses standard
                      mime multipart and base64 encoding, which allows you
                      to exchange files with PC based software like Eudora
                      and NetScape's Mozilla mailer.

                      Fixed a bug in the tooltype parsing code.

                      Numerous minor bug fixes, optimizations and enhancements.

                      The unregistered version of NetGate now shows the
                      "please register" banner only at the beginning of a
                      session. Further, the forced delay of 5 seconds on
                      incoming and outgoing e-mails has been reduced to a 3
                      second delay only on incoming e-mails. There is no
                      delay on outgoing e-mails.

20.04.96    1.2a      NetGate was unable to handle very long POP3 and SMTP
                      server id strings. Internal buffer size increased. Bug
                      introduced in version 1.2.

                      Added some more information to this guide about Mail
                      Manager and how to configure it for use with NetGate.
                      [Pino Aliberti]

07.04.96    1.2       When importing "articles" to a mailing list area,
                      NetGate now always sets the REPLYADDR field to the
                      poster's address. That should make matrix replies a
                      great deal easier.

                      NetGate would crash the system if an incoming news
                      article had a From: field with '@domain (user name)'
                      (i.e. a malformed address without the username part
                      before the '@'). The routine responsible for this was
                      also called at the wrong time. Fixed. [Lars Lindström]

                      Recompiled with SAS/C 6.56 (was using 6.55 before)

                      The internal "content-transfer-encoding" field was
                      not being cleared between mails, which meant that if
                      you received a MIME encoded mail followed by a mail
                      with no content-transfer-encoding header, NetGate
                      would attempt to de-MIME the latter anyway.

                      Increased internal read buffer size for news imports.
                      This should theoretically improve NNTP performance
                      but the effect may not be that obvious because of
                      slow news servers etc.

                      Rephrased a few log- and status messages

                      NetGate now examines both the From: and the Reply-to:
                      lines when checking for mail from a mailing list.

                      If a mail had an incorrect Lines: header, causing
                      NetGate to miss the end-of-mail token and a timeout
                      error to occur, NetGate would flag this as a fatal
                      error and leave the mail on the POP server for later
                      retrieval (the error would obviously repeat itself in
                      every subsequent session). It now only warns about
                      this and deletes the mail from the mail server
                      anyway. [Pino Aliberti]

                      Fixed a major bug in the TCP/IP server interface
                      routines. An internal character buffer was set too
                      short and frequently overflowed, causing system
                      lockups and similar havoc. It has now been quadrupled
                      to allow for any imaginable scenario.

                      The Fidonet TOPT kludge now does not not include a
                      colon. [Pino Aliberti]

                      The AREA: tag now does not have any blanks between
                      itself and the Fidonet echomail area name. This
                      was causing various problems for Mail Manager users
                      (and others as well, I'm sure). [Pino Aliberti]

                      When looking for incoming mail to a mailing list,
                      NetGate was incorrectly examining only the reply
                      address header line (if present), ignoring the "From"
                      line. This could cause problems with some mailing
                      lists. NetGate now looks at both the From:, To: and
                      the Reply-to: lines when testing a mail for mailing
                      list relevance. [Lars Lindström]

                      NetGate refused to send out anything from mailing
                      list echomail areas if you had not defined a default
                      reply address. Fixed.

                      NetGate now uses HELO when sending e-mails. That
                      should solve the problems some people have reported
                      to have with various mail servers and put an end
                      to authentication warnings.

                      NetGate now knows how to handle ESMTP greetings.

                      German installation script kindly provided by
                      Pieter Hollants (fxmts205@rz.uni-frankfurt.de).

                      Italiano installation script kindly provided by
                      Francesco Dipietromaria (dpm@ns.sinet.it)

02.03.96    1.1       NetGate was creating fidonet AREA: with an IFNA
                      kludge. This is technically incorrect and would
                      cause some mailers to import echomail into the
                      netmail area. Fixed. [Jonas Kjellin]

                      The log entry for connects to the mail server
                      incorrectly displayed the name of the news server
                      in stead of the mail server. Fixed.

                      Session connect time is now reported.

                      Fixed a few minor logging problems.

                      Improved ^C handling.

                      Mailing list support! (popular request)

                      Changed shareware restrictions a bit. Please consult
                      the section on @{"how to register" LINK Reg} for details.

                      Internal state machines cleaned up and optimized.

                      Fixed a bug with moderated newsgroups that could cause
                      some areas not to be processed for new articles.

                      Improved timeout code to prevent NetGate from waiting
                      indefinitely for UseNet news articles in some
                      situations.

                      Added a WINDOW tooltype.

                      NetGate now allows different POP3 and SMTP hosts.
                      See the new @{"SMAILHOST" LINK SMAILHOST} keyword (also see the old
                      @{"MAILHOST" LINK MAILHOST} keyword).

                      One some server types NetGate did not work properly
                      and typically failed with a shower of very peculiar
                      error messages. The problem has been identified and a
                      fix is now in place. [Paul Brownlow and others]

                      NGCatchup now logs events like NetGate does.

                      And because of that, NGCatchup no longer has a
                      VERBOSE template keyword.

                      Numerous minor fixes and improvements.

       Note: From the exceptionally low number of registrations I have
       received so far (two, over a two month period), I am beginning to
       think that there really is no need for this kind of program. I am
       seriously considering to drop any further public releases, because
       if nobody feels it's worth buying, then I really don't see why I
       should keep spending precious online time testing and developing it
       for you guys. I'm not made of money, you know.

24.01.96    1.0       First public release. Enjoy! :)

19.11.95    1.0ß      Internal beta releases
@EndNode

@Node NGCatchup "The NGCatchup Utility"
@{u}Using NGCatchup@{uu}

NGCatchup is a small utility which is used to maintain the active-file (see
the @{"configuration section" LINK Configuration}), which contains a list of newsgroups and their
respective highwatermarks (numbers of the last retrieved articles from each
newsgroup).

As explained elsewhere in this document, the active-file is a regular text
file and may be edited using any text editor. However, in most cases you do
not know the range of articles at your news server, so you do not know what
to enter as highwatermarks. This is what the NGCatchup utility is for. It
polls your news server and lets you update your highwatermarks using
numbers relative to the server's own highwatermarks ("set the highwatermark
so I will receive the 20 most recent articles").

NGCatchup may be run from CLI only at the moment. A Workbench/GUI version
is in the works.

When run, NGCatchup first reads your NetGate configuration file to
determine the name of your news host, which newsgroups you subscribe to, et
cetera. It then opens the active file and updates highwatermarks according
to your commandline arguments.

NGCatchup uses the following CLI template:

@{b}NGCatchup@{ub} @{u}CONFIG/K,NEWSGROUP/A/M,BELOW/N,NEW/S@{uu}

The @{u}CONFIG@{uu} parameter allows you to specify the name of NetGate's main
configuration file. It defaults to 'PROGDIR:NetGate.config'.

The obligatory @{u}NEWSGROUP@{uu} argument tells NGCatchup which newsgroup or
newsgroups to process. Wildcards are valid, and "#?" matches all
newsgroups. As indicated by the /M modifier it is possible to enter
multiple arguments, for example:

  @{b}NGCatchup NetGate.config "alt.#?" "comp.#?" BELOW 50@{ub}

  (Note: The quotes are there to allow non-dos shells like Csh to parse the
  line without expanding the arguments)

The @{u}BELOW@{uu} argument tells NGCatchup how many messages below the news
server's own highwater mark you want to set your own highwater mark. In
other words, how many messages you want to receive when you subsequently
poll for news.

  Example:

  @{b}NGCatchup NetGate.config "#?" BELOW 50@{ub}

  This will set the highwatermarks of all configured newsgroups to 50 below
  the server's internal highwatermarks. When you poll next, you should
  receive the last 50 articles in each of the newsgroups you subscribe to.

  Note: If your @{u}existing@{uu} highwatermark is higher than (more recent than) 50
  below the server highwatermark, it will be set back anyway. This means
  you may receive some articles again! See the NEW keyword for a way to
  avoid this.

The @{u}NEW@{uu} switch tells NGCatchup never to move your highwatermarks back in
time (i.e. subtract from it). This is especially useful in connection with
the BELOW keyword, for example in a situation like this:

  @{b}NGCatchup NetGate.config "#?" BELOW 50 NEW@{ub}

  This will set the highwatermarks of all configured newsgroups to 50 below
  the server's internal highwatermarks, but only if your existing
  highwatermarks are even older (smaller) than that.

  The above example is what you typically do if like me you only poll every
  once in a while, like once a week or so. In this case it will set the
  highwatermarks so that you receive maximum 50 new articles from every
  newsgroup you subscribe to. Highwatermarks for newsgroups which are not
  very active and have only received a few new articles will remain
  at their current levels. Highwatermarks for very active newsgroups which
  have had a flow of more than 50 new articles since you last polled will
  be advanced to 50 below the server highwatermarks, skipping all articles
  between that and your existing highwatermark.

When you add a new newsgroup to your configuration file, you probably want
to catch up to the most recent articles and threads in that group. You can
do that in the following way:

  @{b}NGCatchup NetGate.config "<the name of the new newsgroup>" BELOW 100@{ub}

Note: To point out the obvious, NGCatchup only updates your newsgroup
highwatermarks. To actually receive articles you need to use NetGate
itself (duh!).
@EndNode

@Node NGWatch "The NGWatch Utility"
@{u}Using NGWatch@{uu}

NGWatch is a small supplementary program designed to continuously scan for
new incoming e-mail.

When launched NGWatch connects to your mail server, and if it finds any
mail for you it displays a requester and optionally executes a command of
your choice. It subsequently proceeds to scan for new mail at fixed
intervals, displaying a requester and optionally executing another command
as soon as new mail is detected.

NGWatch is a standard Commodities Exchange object and as such may be
controlled via the "Exchange" system utility. The only other way to stop
the program is by running it again (i.e. it works as a toggle or a switch
if you like).

NGWatch will function without the TCP/IP network, in which case it does
nothing. This means that you can launch it from your startup sequence or
from WBStartup even though you may not have started a TCP/IP protocol stack
such as @{"AmiTCP" LINK AmiTCP} or @{"Miami" LINK Miami} at that time. NGWatch will only do its stuff when
the TCP/IP network is up.

NGWatch may be run from a CLI or Shell script, or from the Workbench. When
run from Workbench any parameters must be passed via tooltypes, all of
which are provided in template form in the distribution icon.

The following command line template is used:

@{b}NGWatch@{ub} @{u}CONFIG/K,NEWMAIL,OLDMAIL,INTERVAL/N,NOREQ/S,WINDOW/K@{uu}

The @{u}CONFIG@{uu} parameter allows you to specify the name of NetGate's main
configuration file. It defaults to 'PROGDIR:NetGate.config'. Note that if
you put NGWatch in WBStartup you may need to specify the correct location
of the configuration file.

The @{u}NEWMAIL@{uu} parameter is any valid executable shell command. If specified
the command will be executed when new mail on the mail server is detected.
Command redirection is allowed.

The @{u}OLDMAIL@{uu} parameter is any valid executable shell command. If specified
the command is executed if new mail on the server is detected when NGWatch
is first launched. Command redirection is allowed.

The @{u}INTERVAL@{uu} parameter allows you to specify the delay (in seconds) between
mail checks. It defaults to 60 seconds. Values less than 30 seconds are
generally not recommendable.

The @{u}NOREQ@{uu} parameter allows you to suppress all requesters. Useful for
unattended operation.

The @{u}WINDOW{uu} parameter allows you to specify the window used to display the output
from commands executed by NGWatch.

Examples:

1> Run NGWatch oldmail "execute >nil: mail:rexx/import" interval 40

2> Run NGWatch "NetGate >nil: nogetnews noputnews noputmail"

3> Run NGWatch

In the first example NGWatch is used to launch a script called 'import' if
mail is present at the mail server when the program is launched.
Subsequently you will be notified by requester when new mail is ready on
the mail server (but no command is executed).

The second example shows how to retrieve mail as soon as it appears on the
mail server. In an actual setup you would probably want to launch your mail
scanner and begin the import, too.

The third, very simple example will keep you posted about new mail by using
requesters. No commands are executed.
@EndNode

@Node Tips "Tips & Trix"
@{u}Some ideas for the advanced NetGate user@{uu}

This section is intended to provide "advanced" users with helpful
information on how to use the NetGate in ways which aren't immediately
obvious. The section is a bit meager at the moment but as YOU write me with
stories on how you managed to do something creative with NetGate I will
include these stories here, so others may also benefit from your
experiences.

@{u}1. Tip: Gating multiple newsgroups into the same fidonet echomail area@{uu}

It is possible to direct news from different newsgroups into the same
echomail area. This is useful in connection with the alt.binaries.*
hierachy where you can collect all the files (files, pictures etc) in a
single echomail area for easy managing within your Fidonet scanner.

The same tip applies for mailing lists. It is also possible to direct the
flow from both mailing lists and newsgroups into the same area.

One thing to bear in mind, however, is that any replies you make to one
such "common" echomail area will go to some unpredictable destination.
Typically it is the first defined "feeder" into the area, but that may
change. So the technique is most useful with areas where you generally do
not reply to anything.
@EndNode

@Node Errors "NetGate Error Messages"
@{u}Typical NetGate Error Messages@{uu}

When using NetGate you will undoubtedly receive error messages from time to
time. Most of these should be pretty obvious, but a few deserve a more
detailed description.

@{b}No socket.@{ub}

    This TCP/IP related error message usually means you are running short
    on memory. In any event, the TCP/IP protocol stack cannot create
    a connection handle for use with later mail and news connections.

@{b}Unable to locate <mail/news> host.@{ub}

    The news and/or mail host you have specified in your NetGate
    configuration file does not exist. You probably misspelled it.
    Another less likely reason is that the DNS configuration in your TCP/IP
    protocol stack is incorrect or that the DNS is down for some reason.

@{b}Unable to connect to <mail/news> server.@{ub}
or
@{b}Service currently unavailable at <site>@{ub}

    The news and/or mail host does exist, but does not allow a mail-
    and/or news connection to be made at this time. Pick up the phone
    and dial your Internet provider and ask them what's going on.

@{b}No TCP/IP service available.@{ub}

    NetGate requires a TCP/IP protocol stack such as @{"AmiTCP 3+" LINK AmiTCP} or @{"Miami" LINK Miami}.
    Demo versions of both are available from AmiNet.

@{b}Invalid password.@{ub}
or
@{b}Invalid UserID.@{ub}

    The user-id and/or password in your NetGate configuration file are
    incorrect. Most likely you've made a typing error.

    Note: News- and mail hosts are generally picky regarding case in
    usernames and passwords. Be sure to spell your username and password
    EXACTLY as instructed by your Internet provider.

@{b}Mail error: <error code here>!@{ub}
or
@{b}News error: <error code here>!@{ub}

    Something's gone completely haywire during transmission. Re-run
    NetGate with the same parameters, and if that does not fix things try
    shutting down and restarting the TCP/IP connection before attempting
    again.
    See the @{"Bugs section" LINK Bugs} for some possible alternative reasons.

@{b}Unable to create inbound fidonet packet.@{ub}

    NetGate can't create a Fidonet packet. Most likely you misspelled the
    name of the Fidonet inbound directory in the NetGate configuration
    file. Alternatively it may be one of the more trivial errors such as
    insufficient disk space, write-protected disk etc.

@{b}Group highwatermark incorrect on news host@{ub}

    This warning may appear during news polling and indicates that the
    highwatermark for the current newsgroup points to an article which for
    some reason no longer exists on the news server (news articles are
    deleted regulary to free up disk space).

    After this message NetGate begins to scan the newsgroup to find the
    next valid article. This takes a short while and is concluded with the
    following acknowledgement:

    @{b}Group highwatermark changed from <X> to <Y>@{ub}

    Where X represents the previous highwatermark and Y the new one located
    by NetGate.

@{b}Group session limit reached, articles may remain.@{ub}

    If you define a bytecount-limit for a newsgroup (see the @{"NEWSGROUP" LINK NEWSGROUP}
    configuration keyword in the @{"configuration section" LINK Configuration}), you will get this
    warning when approximately said amount of bytes have been retrieved,
    and NetGate will proceed to the next newsgroup.

    You may receive the remainder of articles (or the next chunk of
    articles) by polling again.

@{b}Warning: Null operation.@{ub}

    You have activated NetGate with a set of command line arguments that
    tell NetGate not to do anything at all. I.e. not deliver or retrieve
    either news or mail. What were you thinking? :-)

    Note: It is possible to invoke NetGate with only the WAIT parameter.
    See the @{"Usage" LINK Usage} section for a description of the WAIT parameter.
@EndNode

@Node Miami "Miami"
Excerpts from the Miami docs:

Introduction
************

   Miami is an integrated TCP/IP system for AmigaDOS, that allows you
to access the Internet by modem in a very simple way.

   Miami is based on the latest version (4.4BSD V2) of the official BSD
networking code, i.e. Miami contains a "true" and complete TCP/IP
stack, not just an emulation that only supports parts of the TCP/IP
standard.

   The application programmers' interface of Miami is compatible with
that of AmiTCP 4.x (@{b}bsdsocket.library@{ub}), i.e. most of the programs
written and compiled for AmiTCP 4.x will work with Miami without any
modification and without recompiling.

   In addition, Miami has a built-in dialer that can be used both in
script-driven and interactive mode, an implementation of the (C)SLIP
and PPP protocols, a graphical user interface for program control and
configuration.

   Miami also has a built-in implementation of @{b}inetd@{ub}, the "Internet
super-server", with several built-in services including "fingerd" and
"identd", a built-in implementation of @{b}TCP:@{ub}, the AmigaDOS stream
handler for TCP/IP, and a built-in implementation of usergroup.library,
the interface to manage users and user groups.

   Unlike other general-purpose protocol stacks Miami is specifically
targetted towards users who use a modem to access the Internet. The
configuration process is made as simple as possible: most of the
configuration parameters are determined by Miami automatically.  Miami
also supports preconfigured settings that can be distributed by
Internet providers.

   Miami uses MUI 3.3 or higher for its user interface, i.e. you must
have MUI installed before you can use Miami.

[...]

Usage / Copying
***************

   Miami is shareware. In this case this means that a personalized key
file is required to use the full functionality of Miami.

[...]

Support
*******

   There are several ways to get technical support, updates etc.:

@{b}email@{ub}
     kruse@mail.nordicglobal.com

@{b}snail mail@{ub}
     Holger Kruse
     12006 Coed Drive
     Orlando FL 32826
     USA

@{b}WWW@{ub}
     http://www.nordicglobal.com/Miami.html

@{b}mailing list@{ub}
     send "SUBSCRIBE miami-ml" in the body of a mail to
     "amiga-lists@mail.nordicglobal.com".
@EndNode

